==English==

===Etymology===
Conjunction of {{m|en|sage}} (unhurt) and {{m|en|sound}} (whole, unhurt). Compare with Old French {{m|fr|sauf et sain}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Having come to no [[harm]], especially after being exposed to [[danger]].
#* '''1594''', [[w:William_Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''The Comedy of Errors'', act 4, scene 4,
#*: Fetch our stuff from thence:
#*: I long that we were '''safe and sound''' aboard.

====Synonyms====
* {{l|en|in one piece}}, {{l|en|unharmed}}, {{l|en|unhurt}}, {{l|en|uninjured}}, {{l|en|unscathed}}

